<validation>
1. Demonstrate homograph attack bypassing visual inspection.
2. Show normalization-based filter bypass.
3. Prove case mapping vulnerability with locale differences.
4. Document invisible character injection.
5. Provide specific Unicode code points used in attack.
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Proper Unicode normalization before comparison
- Homograph detection in domain names
- Stripping of zero-width characters
- Locale-aware case comparison
- IDN restriction to single script
- Consistent encoding handling
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Phishing via lookalike domains/usernames
- Authentication and authorization bypass
- Filter and WAF evasion
- Log poisoning and forensic evasion
- Data integrity issues
- User confusion and social engineering
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always test with Cyrillic lookalike characters.
2. Check if normalization happens before or after validation.
3. Test fullwidth equivalents for special characters.
4. Use online Unicode analyzers to identify character codes.
5. Test invisible character insertion in all string inputs.
6. Check for RTL override in filenames and messages.
7. Verify case comparison is locale-independent.
8. Test encoding detection with mixed encodings.
9. Look for length validation before normalization.
10. Document exact Unicode code points for reproducibility.
</pro_tips>

<remember>Unicode security issues stem from the gap between visual representation and actual byte content. What looks identical may be different, and what looks different may be equivalent after normalization. Always test with various Unicode representations of the same visual content.</remember>
</unicode_normalization_guide>
